  "prompt": "When and how did WWI start and end?",
  "response": "World War I, also known as the First World War or the Great War, spanned from **July 28, 1914**, to **November 11, 1918**. Here's a brief overview of how it began and concluded:\n\n### **Start of World War I (July 28, 1914):**\n\n1. **Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand:**\n   - On **June 28, 1914**, Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary and his wife were assassinated in Sarajevo by Gavrilo Princip, a Bosnian Serb nationalist associated with the group **Black Hand**.\n   \n2. **Escalation Through Alliances:**\n   - The assassination set off a chain reaction among Europe's intricate system of alliances. Austria-Hungary, seeking to assert its influence in the Balkans, issued an ultimatum to Serbia, which led to Austria-Hungary declaring war on Serbia on July 28, 1914.\n   - Russia mobilized in support of Serbia, prompting Germany to declare war on Russia on August 1, 1914.\n   - Germany then declared war on Russia's ally, France, and invaded Belgium to execute the Schlieffen Plan, leading Britain to declare war on Germany on August 4, 1914.\n\n3. **Global Involvement:**\n   - The conflict quickly expanded as nations from around the world joined based on their alliances, transforming what could have been a localized conflict into a global war.\n\n### **End of World War I (November 11, 1918):**\n\n1. **Armistice Agreement:**\n   - Exhausted by years of trench warfare, massive casualties, and economic strain, the Central Powers (primarily Germany, Austria-Hungary, the Ottoman Empire, and Bulgaria) began seeking peace.\n   - On **November 11, 1918**, an armistice was signed between the Allies and Germany at Compi\u00e8gne, France, effectively ceasing hostilities at the 11th hour of the 11th day of the 11th month.\n\n2. **Treaty of Versailles (June 28, 1919):**\n   - While the armistice ended the fighting, the official conclusion of the war came with the signing of the **Treaty of Versailles** on June 28, 1919.\n   - The treaty imposed heavy reparations and territorial losses on Germany, redrew national boundaries in Europe, and established the League of Nations in an effort to prevent future conflicts.\n\n### **Key Factors Leading to the War:**\n\n- **Militarism:** European nations engaged in an arms race, building up large militaries and stockpiling weapons.\n- **Alliances:** Complex alliances created a domino effect, where the conflict between two nations could involve others.\n- **Imperialism:** Competition for overseas colonies heightened tensions among the great powers.\n- **Nationalism:** Intense national pride and ethnic tensions contributed to the desire for independence and dominance.\n\nWorld War I fundamentally reshaped the political landscape of the 20th century, leading to the downfall of empires, significant geopolitical changes, and setting the stage for World War II.",
